results.notes:
07/19/2019
Minnetrista, Minnesota (Hennepin County)

Amanita vaginata

- Ecology: Growing beneath (almost seemingly attached) an oak tree. The tree was the last tree before a ditch leading to a road began. This meant much of the ground was disturbed. The forest the road cuts through is mixed (with maple, cottonwood and oak prevelant).

- Cap: 8.5cm (with striations visible at 1.5cm). Grayish/tawny color. Pretty flat with dark umbo in the center.

- Gills: Not attached (free from stem). Off-white/Whitish Tan color. Smaller gills present amongst closely arranged full size gills. Appearing to have a jagged appearance on edge.

- Stem: About 15cm long (1.5cm thick). Slightly striate or tufted appearance with off-white to tan color. Sac/tube-like volva with reddish brown/tan discoloring.

- Spore print: White
